### B

*   **[Babbitt](/Babbitt_(alloy))** – A type of [alloy](/Alloy) used for [bearing surfaces](/Bearing_surface) in [plain bearings](/Plain_bearing). Invented in 1839, it's a material designed to facilitate smooth, low-friction movement.

*   **[Backdrive](/Backdrive)** – A component designed to operate in reverse, taking its input from what would normally be its output. It’s a concept that extends across many systems, allowing for reverse operation or control.

*   **[Backlash](/Backlash_(gear))** – The clearance or "play" in a mechanism due to gaps between parts, particularly between gear teeth. It’s the space where movement happens without engaging the next part. Defined as the maximum distance or angle a part can move before applying appreciable force to the next. It’s the looseness in the system.

*   **[Balancing machine](/Balancing_machine)** – A tool for ensuring that rotating parts – rotors, fans, [turbines](/Turbine) – don't vibrate excessively. It measures imbalances and allows for corrections, ensuring smooth operation. It’s about achieving equilibrium in motion.

*   **[Ball detent](/Ball_detent)** – A simple mechanism to temporarily lock a moving part in place. Usually involves a ball held under spring tension, fitting into a recess. It’s a temporary pause, a held position.

*   **[Ball screw](/Ball_screw)** – A mechanical linear actuator that converts rotational motion into linear motion with minimal [friction](/Friction). It uses [ball bearings](/Ball_bearing) in a threaded shaft to achieve this, allowing for high thrust loads with little internal resistance. Precision in motion.

*   **[Ball spline](/Ball_spline)** – A specialized linear motion bearing that allows for near-frictionless linear movement while simultaneously transmitting torque. It involves grooves on a shaft and recirculating balls. It’s linear motion with a twist – the ability to also rotate.

*   **[Beale number](/Beale_number)** – A parameter used to characterize the performance of [Stirling engines](/Stirling_engine). It gives an indication of the power output. Higher numbers suggest better performance, especially with large temperature differentials.

*   **[Bearing](/Bearing_(mechanical))** – A machine element that constrains motion to only the desired paths, and importantly, reduces [friction](/Friction) between moving parts. It's the facilitator of smooth movement.

*   **[Bearing pressure](/Bearing_pressure)** – The contact pressure between surfaces, particularly when a convex surface meets a concave one. Excessive pressure can lead to wear and deformation, a common cause of bearing failure. It’s the force distributed over an area.

*   **[Bearing surface](/Bearing_surface)** – The area where two objects make contact. It’s relevant in everything from [bolted joints](/Bolted_joint) to [bearings](/Bearing_(mechanical)). It’s the interface of contact and load.

*   **[Belt](/Belt_(mechanical))** – A loop of material used to connect rotating [shafts](/Drive_shaft) mechanically, usually for transmitting [power](/Transmission_(mechanics)). They ride on [pulleys](/Pulley) and are a common way to transfer motion.

*   **[Belt friction](/Belt_friction)** – The friction experienced by a [belt](/Belt_(mechanical)) wrapped around a surface. It's what allows a belt to transmit force effectively, and it’s modeled by the [Belt friction equation](/Capstan_equation).

*   **[Bending](/Bending)** – The behavior of a structural element when subjected to a [load](/Structural_load) perpendicular to its longitudinal axis. It’s [applied mechanics](/Applied_mechanics) in action, causing flexure.

*   **[Biomechatronics](/Biomechatronics)** – The integration of [biology](/Biology), [mechanics](/Mechanics), and [electronics](/Electronics). It’s about creating devices that interface with living systems, from [prosthetic limbs](/Prosthesis) to systems that support respiration or vision.

*   **[Body in white](/Body_in_white)** – (BIW) The stage in [automobile manufacturing](/Automotive_industry) where the car's body structure is assembled, before painting or the addition of mechanical components. It's the bare skeleton.

*   **[Bogie](/Bogie)** – A framework carrying a [wheelset](/Wheelset_(rail_transport)), attached to a vehicle. It's a modular subassembly of wheels and [axles](/Axle). Think of the wheeled structures under train cars.

*   **[Bonded seal](/Bonded_seal)** – A type of [washer](/Washer_(hardware)) used to create a seal around a screw or bolt. Also known as Dowty seals, they're a common, effective sealing solution.

*   **[Brittleness](/Brittleness)** – The tendency of a material to fracture without significant [plastic deformation](/Plastic_Deformation) when subjected to [stress](/Stress_(physics)). Brittle materials absorb little [energy](/Energy) before breaking. They snap.

*   **[Buckling](/Buckling)** – A [failure mode](/Structural_failure) characterized by sudden sideways deflection under [compressive](/Compression_(physics)) [stress](/Stress_(mechanics)). It can happen even when the material's stress capacity hasn't been reached. It's a sudden loss of stability.

*   **[Bus](/Bus)** – A [road vehicle](/Road_vehicle) designed to carry many [passengers](/Passenger). A common sight, a workhorse of public transportation.

*   **[Bushing](/Bushing_(isolator))** – A type of [vibration isolator](/Vibration_isolation), often made of [rubber](/Rubber) or [polyurethane](/Polyurethane). It sits between two parts, damping vibrations and allowing controlled movement. Common in [vehicle suspension](/Suspension_(vehicle)) systems.

*   **[Boiler](/Boiler)** – A closed [vessel](/Pressure_vessel) where a [fluid](/Fluid), usually water, is heated. It's a fundamental component for [water heating](/Boiler_(water_heating)), [central heating](/Central_heating), and [power generation](/Boiler_(power_generation)).

