### F

*   **[Fits and tolerances](/Fits_and_tolerances)** – (This entry is blank. A critical concept in mechanical engineering, referring to the allowable variation in dimensions for mating parts. Its absence is notable.)

*   **[Factor of safety](/Factor_of_safety)** – A multiplier applied to the expected load to ensure a structure or component can withstand more than its anticipated stress. It’s a margin for error, a safety net.

*   **[False precision](/False_precision)** – (This entry is also blank. It likely refers to presenting data with more precision than is actually justified.)

*   **[Fast fracture](/Fast_fracture)** – (Blank. Refers to rapid crack propagation, a dangerous failure mode.)

*   **[Fatigue](/Fatigue_(material))** – The weakening of a material caused by repeatedly applied loads, even if those loads are below the material's [yield strength](/Yield_strength). It’s the cumulative damage from cyclic stress.

*   **[Fillet](/Fillet_(mechanics))** – A rounded internal corner, often used to strengthen a part by reducing stress concentrations. It’s a subtle curve that prevents breakage.

*   **[First law of thermodynamics](/First_law_of_thermodynamics)** – The law of [energy](/Energy) conservation. [Energy](/Energy) can be converted from one form to another, but it cannot be created or destroyed.

*   **[Finite element analysis](/Finite_element_analysis)** – (FEA) A computational method used to predict how a product reacts to real-world forces, vibration, heat, [fluid flow](/Fluid_flow), and other physical effects. It breaks down complex structures into smaller elements.

*   **[Flange](/Flange)** – A projecting rim or edge, used to increase strength, facilitate attachment, or guide. Common in pipes and structural components.

*   **[Fluid mechanics](/Fluid_mechanics)** – The study of [fluids](/Fluid) (liquids, gases, and plasmas) in [motion](/Motion_(physics)) and at rest, and the forces acting on them.

*   **[Flywheel](/Flywheel)** – A rotating mechanical device used to store rotational [energy](/Energy). It smooths out power delivery by absorbing and releasing kinetic energy.

*   **[Force](/Force)** – An influence that can cause an object with [mass](/Mass) to change its [velocity](/Velocity), i.e., to [accelerate](/Accelerate). It has both [magnitude](/Euclidean_vector) and [direction](/Direction_(geometry)), making it a [vector](/Vector_(geometric)) quantity.

*   **[Force density](/Force_density)** – (Blank. Likely refers to force per unit volume or mass.)

*   **[Forging](/Forging)** – A manufacturing process involving the shaping of metal using localized compressive forces. It’s a method of plastic deformation.

*   **[Four-bar linkage](/Four-bar_linkage)** – A common mechanical linkage consisting of four rigid bodies connected by [hinges](/Hinge). It's a fundamental mechanism for converting motion.

*   **[Four-stroke cycle](/Four-stroke_cycle)** – The sequence of events in a [reciprocating engine](/Reciprocating_engine) involving intake, compression, power, and exhaust strokes.

*   **[Four wheel drive](/Four_wheel_drive)** – A drivetrain that engages all four wheels of a vehicle for propulsion.

*   **[Friction](/Friction)** – The [force](/Force) that opposes the relative motion of surfaces in contact. It can be static (between stationary surfaces) or kinetic (between moving surfaces). It’s the resistance to motion.

*   **[Front wheel drive](/Front_wheel_drive)** – A drivetrain configuration where only the front wheels are driven.

*   **[Fundamentals of Engineering exam](/Fundamentals_of_Engineering_exam)** – (FE exam) A standardized exam required for [professional engineer](/Professional_engineer) licensure in the United States.

*   **[Fusible plug](/Fusible_plug)** – A safety device in [boilers](/Boiler) designed to melt and release steam if the water level drops too low.

*   **[Fusion deposition modelling](/Fusion_Deposition_Modelling)** – A 3D printing process where material is deposited layer by layer. Also known as fused filament fabrication.

